{{Infobox connector | name = TOSLINK / EIAJ optical | type = Optical digital audio connector | image = [[Image:TOS LINK clear cable.jpg|300px]] | logo = | caption = Clear TOSLINK cable with a round connector for [[S/PDIF]] connectivity. | designer = [[Toshiba]] | design_date = 1983 | manufacturer = [[Toshiba]] | production_date = Since 1983 | superseded = | superseded_by = | superseded_by_date = | external = Yes | hotplug = Yes | length = | width = | height = | audio_signal = Digital audio bitstream. Originally limited to 48 kHz at 20 bits. Extended to support all modern formats (Depending on manufacture and specification) | data_bit_width = 32-bit audio packets | data_bandwidth = Originally 3.1&nbsp;Mbit/s; now 125&nbsp;Mbit/s | data_devices = 1 | data_style = Serial | cable = [[Optical fiber]], ~{{convert|10|m|abbr=on}} maximum<ref name="length">{{ cite web | url = http://www.epanorama.net/documents/audio/spdif.html | title = S/PDIF Interface Document | accessdate = 2009-02-16 | author = epanorama.net | dateformat = }}</ref> | physical_connector = JIS F05 (JIS C5974-1993 F05) | num_pins = 1 | pinout_image = | pinout_caption = | pin1 = | pin1_name = | pinout_notes = }}
'''TOSLINK''' (from ''Toshiba Link''<ref name='TOTX1701_spec'>[http://www.semicon.toshiba.co.jp/openb2b/websearch/productDetails.jsp?partKey=TOTX1701%28F%29 Toshiba TOTX1701] TOSLINK Transmitter Module specifications.</ref>) is a standardized [[optical fiber connector]] system.<ref name='toshiba_what_is_toslink'>[http://www.semicon.toshiba.co.jp/eng/product/opto/faq/toslink/answer_toslink01.html "What Is TOSLINK?"] Toshiba Toslink FAQs.</ref> Also known generically as an "'''optical audio cable'''" or just "'''optical cable'''", its most common use is in consumer [[Sound recording|audio]] equipment (via a "digital optical" socket), where it carries a [[digital audio]] stream from components such as [[Compact disc|CD]] and [[DVD]] players, [[Digital Audio Tape|DAT]] recorders, computers, and modern [[video game console]]s, to an [[AV receiver]] that can decode two channels of uncompressed lossless [[PCM audio]] or {{nowrap|[[Audio compression (data)|compressed]] 5.1/7.1}} [[surround sound]] such as [[Dolby Digital]] or [[DTS (sound system)|DTS Surround System]]. Unlike [[HDMI]], TOSLINK does not have the bandwidth to carry the lossless versions of [[Dolby TrueHD]], [[DTS-HD Master Audio]], or more than two channels of [[PCM audio]].
Although TOSLINK supports several different media formats and physical standards, digital audio connections using the rectangular [[Electronic Industries Association of Japan|EIAJ]]/[[Japan Electronics and Information Technology Industries Association|JEITA]] RC-5720 (also CP-1201 and JIS C5974-1993 F05) connector are by far the most common.<ref name="digikey_toshiba">{{cite web|title=Product guide, Fiber-Optic Devices TOSLINK(tm)|url=http://www.digikey.com/Web%20Export/Supplier%20Content/Toshiba_264/PDF/Toshiba_BCE0037_catalog.pdf}} 100621 digikey.com</ref> The optical signal is a red light with a peak wavelength of {{nowrap|650 nm.}}<ref name='TOTX1701_spec'/> Depending on the [[modulation|type of modulated signal]] being carried, other optical wavelengths may be present.<!-- Digi-Key hints at 650 nm, but Engdahl hints at 660 nm --><ref name="digikey_toshiba" />
== History == {{Ref improve section|date=January 2011}} [[File:TOSLINK.jpg|thumb|left|TOSLINK connector (JIS F05)]]
[[Toshiba]] originally created TOSLINK to connect their CD players to the [[audio receiver|receiver]]s they manufactured, for [[Pulse-code modulation|PCM]] audio streams. The software layer is based on the "Sony Philips Digital Interconnect Format" ([[S/PDIF]]), while the hardware layer utilizes a fiber optic transmission system, rather than the electrical (copper) hardware layer of S/PDIF. TOSLINK was soon adopted by manufacturers of most CD players. It can often be found on video source (DVD and Blu-ray players, cable boxes and game consoles) to connect the digital audio stream to [[Dolby Digital]]/[[Digital Theatre System|DTS]] decoders.
The name is a registered trademark of Toshiba, created from ''TOShiba-LINK''. Variations of the name, such as ''TOSlink'', ''TosLink'', and ''Tos-link'', are also seen, while the official generic name for the standard is ''EIAJ optical''.
[[ADAT Lightpipe]] or simply ADAT Optical uses an optical transmission system similar to TOSLINK, and is used in the professional music/audio industry. While the ADAT Lightpipe format uses the same JIS F05 connectors as TOSLINK, the ADAT Lightpipe data format is not compatible with S/PDIF. {{citation needed|date=April 2018}}
== Properties and issues == Due to their high attenuation of light, the effective range of plastic optical cables is limited to {{nowrap|5–10 m}}.<ref name="length"/> They can temporarily fail or be permanently damaged if tightly bent. Although less commonly available and more expensive than plastic optical fiber (POF) cables, glass or silica optical fibers have lower losses and can extend the range of the TOSLINK system.
Optical cables are not susceptible to electrical problems such as [[ground loop (electricity)|ground loops]] and [[RF interference]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.audioholics.com/education/cables/understanding-digital-interconnects |title=Understanding Digital Interconnects |publisher=Audioholics.com |accessdate=2007-07-12 |author=Joseph D. Cornwall |date=December 31, 2004 }}</ref>
== Design == [[Image:Fiber optic illuminated.jpg|thumb|left|A TOSLINK fiber optic audio cable being illuminated on one end]]
Several types of fiber can be used for TOSLINK: inexpensive {{nowrap|1 mm}} plastic optical fiber, higher-quality multistrand plastic optical fibers, or quartz glass optical fibers, depending on the desired bandwidth and application. TOSLINK cables are usually limited to {{nowrap|5 meters}} in length, with a technical maximum<ref name="length" /> of {{nowrap|10 meters,}} for reliable transmission without the use of a signal booster or a repeater. However, it is very common for interfaces on newer consumer electronics (satellite receivers and PCs with optical outputs) to easily run over {{nowrap|30 meters}} on even low-cost {{nowrap|(0.82 USD/m 2009<!--2009-06-19-->)}} TOSLINK cables. TOSLINK transmitters operate at a nominal optical wavelength of {{nowrap|650 nm}} {{nowrap|(~461.2 THz).}}
=== Mini-TOSLINK === [[File:Minitoslink.png|thumb|right|A mini-TOSLINK adapter]] '''Mini-TOSLINK''' is a standardized [[optical fiber connector]] smaller than the standard square TOSLINK connector commonly used in larger consumer [[Sound recording|audio]] equipment. The plug is almost the same size and shape as the ubiquitous [[TRS connector|{{nowrap|3.5 mm}} stereo minijack]]. Adapters are available to connect a full-size TOSLINK plug to a mini-TOSLINK socket. Combined {{nowrap|3.5 mm}} jack and mini-TOSLINK sockets exist which can accept a {{nowrap|3.5 mm}} jack or a mini-TOSLINK plug; mini-TOSLINK plugs are made {{nowrap|0.5 mm}} longer than electrical jack plugs so that the latter are too short to touch and damage the LED of combined connectors. Many [[laptop computer]] and portable digital audio equipment models, such as the [[Google Chromecast Audio]] device<ref name=Pendlebury>{{cite web |url=http://www.cnet.com/news/chromecast-audio-adds-support-for-multi-room-music-and-high-res-files/ |website=[[Cnet]] |title=Chromecast Audio adds support for multiroom music and high-res files |last=Pendlebury |first=Ty |date=December 10, 2015 |archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/6h1ET0BHe |archive-date=April 24, 2016}}</ref><ref name=Greenwald>{{cite web |url=https://www.pcmag.com/article2/0,2817,2492361,00.asp |website=[[PC Magazine]] |title=Google Chromecast Audio |last=Greenwald |first=Will |date=December 14, 2015 |archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/6h1EauDXA |archive-date=April 24, 2016}}</ref> and [[Apple Inc.|Apple]] [[AirPort Express]] and [[iPod Hi-Fi]], use these connectors that allow for the insertion of {{nowrap|3.5 mm}} analog (electrical) headphone output or microphone input or mini-TOSLINK digital (optical) output.
